<item>
            <title>[LU-5622] copytool_cleanup function should check/wait for copytool death</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-5622</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;copytool_cleanup() function of sanity-hsm test suite does not presently check/wait for effective copytool main+fork&apos;ed processes death.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This can be a problem, since a lot of sanity-hsm sub-tests end with a copytool_cleanup() call when next sub-test starts with a copytool_setup() call, and may lead to situations/failures, like in the following auto-tests sessions :&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/2fb4cdd8-3aaa-11e4-a021-5254006e85c2&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/2fb4cdd8-3aaa-11e4-a021-5254006e85c2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/7ff7ee42-2fe2-11e4-9f89-5254006e85c2&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/7ff7ee42-2fe2-11e4-9f89-5254006e85c2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/1bc3d036-311c-11e4-b503-5254006e85c2&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/1bc3d036-311c-11e4-b503-5254006e85c2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/02b03f6c-e761-11e3-9c5d-52540035b04c&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/02b03f6c-e761-11e3-9c5d-52540035b04c&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where next sub-test copytool_setup() attempt will not succeed to restart a new/fresh copytool (but only signal the current/old one from previous sub-test), finally leading to a test failure.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
